orbes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Forbes in Tullynessle, Aberdeenshire, so named from Gaelic <i>forba</i> ‘field, district’ + the locative suffix <i>-ais</i>. The placename is pronounced in two syllables, with the stress on the second, and the surname until recently reflected this. Today, however, it is generally a monosyllable.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Firbhisigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearbhisigh</i>’, a personal name composed of elements meaning ‘man’ + ‘prosperity’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) in Connacht was famous for its traditional historians, compilers of the Book of Lecan."],"variants":[{"name":"Fawbush","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which ispronounced as two syllables in Aberdeenshire. Compare   Forbush  ."]},{"name":"Forbus","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , reflecting thetraditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Forbush","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Forbes  , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Altered form of German <b>Vorbusch</b>, a topographic name for someone living on the edge of a wood, from <i>vor</i> ‘in front of’ + North German <i>Busch</i> ‘wood, bush’."]},{"name":"Fobbs","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Furbush","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which is traditionally pronounced as two syllables. Compare   Furbish  ."]},{"name":"Forbis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Fobes","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Forbess","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":6,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":31,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":44,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"John Forbes was born about 1284, in Devon, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Jane Davis."},"et":{"about 1284–":"umbes 1284–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","1288":"1288","1284":"1284","about 1284":"umbes 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1284–":"noin 1284–Kuollut","1288–Female":"1288–Kuollut","1310–1368":"1310–1368","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","1288":"1288","1284":"1284","about 1284":"noin 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1284–":"environ 1284–Décédé","1288–Female":"1288–Décédée","1310–1368":"13